                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d148">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Conference/154: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-01T19:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 1, 1937—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 1—3:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>683. Your 433, October 31, 2 p.m. communicated orally and confidentially to the
                    Foreign Secretary. He said that it confirmed his view <pb facs="0146" n="138"
                        xml:id="pg_138"/> that statements from this type of Japanese can not be
                    taken as really representing the views or intentions of the Japanese
                    Government.</p>
                <p>Eden leaves tonight for Brussels.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
